The paper discusses community structure in complex networks, which is a topic that falls under the subfield of network science. The focus on analyzing changing community structure across multiple networks suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The use of simulated networks and real networks consisting of teams also suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-categories of cs.SD (Software Engineering) and cs.SOC (Computational Social Science). The method proposed in the paper, scaled inclusivity, involves evaluating the consistency of the classification of every node in a network independently, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
